ARIZONA PUBLIC SERVICE COMPANY MARKET RATE TARIFF NO. 1 (MR-1)
1 DEFINITIONS
The following terms shall have the specified meaning when used in the Market Rate
Tariff No. 1 (Tariff) or in a Service Agreement:
1.1 Commission: The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
1.2 Customer: An entity that executes a Service Agreement under this Tariff.
1.3 Service Agreement: The initial agreement and any supplements thereto entered
into by a Customer and Arizona Public Service Company (APS) for service
under this Tariff.
1.4 Tariff: This Market Rate Tariff No. 1 as it may be amended and/or
superseded from time to time.
1.5 Transaction: An individual transaction scheduled pursuant to this Tariff and a
Service Agreement.
1.6 Party: References to a Party shall mean either APS or the Customer, or
collectively shall be referred to as Parties.
2 AVAILABILITY
2.1 This Tariff is available for sales of electric energy and/or capacity by APS,
subject to restrictions set forth in Sections 2.2 and 2.3.
2.2 Sales of electric energy and/or capacity at market-based rates by APS are
permissible under this tariff in all balancing authority areas where APS has
been granted market-based rate authority. Sales into the California ISO
Energy Imbalance Market are permissible per Section 7.3. Sales under the
Western Power Pool (WPP) Western Resource Adequacy Program
(WRAP) are permissible per Section 7.5. Sales of energy
and capacity under this tariff are also permissible at the metered boundary
between the Sellers mitigated balancing authority area and a balancing authority
area where the Seller has been granted market-based rate authority provided: (i)
the legal title of power sold transfers at the metered boundary of the balancing
authority area where the Seller has market-based rate authority, and; (ii) if the
Seller sells at the metered boundary of a mitigated balancing authority area at
market-based rates, then neither it nor its affiliates can sell into that mitigated
balancing authority area from the outside. APS will retain, for a period of
five years from the date of sale, all data and information related to the sale
that demonstrates compliance with items (i) and (ii) above. Restrictions in this
section do not apply to sales made in the CAISO Energy Imbalance Market.
2.3 APS may sell ancillary services under this tariff as follows:
2.3.1 California: APS offers regulation service, spinning reserve service,
and non- spinning reserve service to the California Independent System
Operator (CAISO) and to others that are self-supplying ancillary
services to the CAISO.
2.3.2 Third-party ancillary services: APS offers Regulation Service, Energy
and Generator , Operating Reserve-Spinning, and Operating Reserve-
Supplemental, and Primary Frequency Response Service. Sales will not
include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that
entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends
on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility
affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying
transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with
the third-party supplier; Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and
Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility
that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access
transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own
customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization.
Sales of Regulation Service will not include sales to a public utility that is
purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission
tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except
at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission providers
OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted
authorization.
3 CHARACTER OF SERVICE
APS may provide capacity and/or energy under this Tariff in varying amounts, at
varying levels of firmness or priorities of service, for varying periods of service,
and in accordance with varying delivery schedules, as agreed to between the Customer
and APS.
4 RATES
4.1 The rates for purchases under this Tariff shall be as agreed to by the Customer
and APS.
4.2 All sales of electric capacity or energy shall be made at rates established by
agreement between the purchaser and APS.
5 SECTION RESERVED
6 SECTION RESERVED
7 LIMITATIONS AND EXEMPTIONS REGARDING MARKET-BASED RATE
AUTHORITY
7.1 APS is not authorized to sell electricity at market-based rates in the APS
Balancing Authority Area (See Arizona Public Service Company, 153 FERC ¶
61,161 (2015)) and the Tucson Electric Power Balancing Authority Area (See
Arizona Public Service Company ER10-2437-012). This limitation is reflected
in Sections 2.2 and 2.3.2 of this Tariff. Restrictions in this section do not apply
to sales made in the CAISO Energy Imbalance Market or the WPP WRAP.
Authorization and restrictions for sales in the CAISO Energy Imbalance Market
are provided in Section 7.3. Authorization and restrictions for sales in the WPP
WRAP are provided in Section 7.5.
7.2 APS has been granted a waiver of the Commission restrictions on: (a) sales of
electricity between affiliates; and (b) sharing of market information between
affiliates. Pinnacle West Capital Corp., 91 FERC ¶ 61,290 (2000), reh'g
denied, 95 FERC ¶ 61,300 (2001). As a result, these restrictions (currently
codified in 18 C.F.R. §§ 35.39(b) and (d)) do not apply to APS.
7.3 For sales into the CAISO Energy Imbalance Market, APS may make sales at
market-based rates under this tariff in all EIM markets for all periods in which
such authority is granted by the Commission. APSs EIM bids may be subject to
mitigation by the CAISO when imports are constrained in accordance with the
market power mitigation terms of the CAISO Tariff.
7.4 Seller is authorized to make sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating
Reserve-Supplemental services, as those terms are defined by the North
American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC), within the Western
Electricity Coordinating Council region to any public utility transmission
provider outside the APS Balancing Authority Area that is purchasing ancillary
services to satisfy its own open-access transmission tariff requirements to offer
ancillary services to its own customers. See Arizona Public Service Company,
Docket No. ER17-2035-000.
7.5 For sales into the WPP WRAP, APS may make sales at market-based rates under this
tariff as mitigated by the WPP WRAP program, which designates pricing in Section 21
of the FERC approved WPP WRAP Tariff. Sales make under this program will not
exceed the applicable pricing established in that section. Northwest Power Pool d/b/a
Western Power Pool, 182 FERC ¶ 61,063 (2023).
7.5.1 The Northwest Subregion is comprised of the following Balancing Authority
Areas: Avista Corporation; BC Hydro and Power Authority; Bonneville Power
Authority; Chelan County PUD #1; Douglas County PUD #1; Grant County PUD #2;
Northwestern Energy; PacifiCorp West; Portland General Electric; Puget Sound
Energy; Seattle City and Light; and Tacoma Power. For the Northwest Subregion: the
Day-Ahead Applicable Index Price is the Intercontinental Exchange, Inc. (ICE) Day-
Ahead (DA) Mid-Columbia (Mid-C) Index. The Real-Time Applicable Index is the
Powerdex real-time Mid-Columbia Index.
7.5.2 The Southwest and East Subregion is comprised of the following Balancing
Authority Areas: Arizona Public Service; Basin Electric; Black Hills, Idaho Power
Company, NV Energy, PacifiCorp East, Public Service Company of New Mexico, and
Salt River Project. For the East and Southwest Subregion: the Day-Ahead Applicable
Index Price is the ICE DA Palo Verde (PV) Index. The Real-Time Applicable Index
Price is the average of the four fifteen-minute market (FMM) results for the Palo Verde
intertie in the California Independent System Operator (CAISO) market (FMM
Scheduling Point / Tie Combination locational marginal price; Node:
PALOVRDE_ASR-APND; Tie: PVWEST).
8 EFFECTIVE DATE
This Tariff shall be effective on the date established by the Commission.
9 COMPLIANCE WITH COMMISSION REGULATIONS
APS shall comply with the provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with
any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning APS market-based rate
authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes APS to engage in
affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits APS market-based rate
authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 CFR Part 35, Subpart H,
and with any orders of the Commission concerning APS market-based rate authority, will
constitute a violation of this tariff.
10 SELLER CATEGORY
APS is a Category 2 seller, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a) in the Southwest Region; APS
is a Category 1 seller, as defined in 18 CFR 35.36(a), in all other regions.
